# Jarvis Desktop Assistant — Architecture & Build Plan

**One Tauri app. Built and tested on macOS. Shipped and running on Windows. Fully local voice pipeline. Animated reactive orb front end.**

---

## 1. What we're building

- A single Tauri 2 application (one codebase, one repo) that compiles natively for both macOS and Windows.
- A Rust-native, always-listening voice pipeline running *inside* the app (no separate server, no Python, no Docker): wake word → voice activity detection → local speech-to-text.
- A "Jarvis" front end: a glowing orb that idles, perks up on wake word, animates while listening, and reacts distinctly when it accepts/processes a command.
- A command dispatcher that takes the transcribed text and forwards it to your agent backend (referred to here as **"open claw"** — see [Section 10](#10-open-decisions) for what I need from you to finish this part).

Everything voice-related runs locally on the user's machine. No audio ever needs to leave the device unless you deliberately choose a cloud STT later.

---

## 2. Architecture at a glance

Tauri's whole value proposition is: **native Rust core + web-tech front end, one process, one binary.** We lean into that fully — no sidecar, no subprocess for the voice pipeline. The voice engine runs as an async background task inside the same Rust core that powers the window.

```
