## 3. Tech stack

| Layer | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| App shell | **Tauri 2** (current stable: v2.10.x) | Small binaries, native performance, one codebase for macOS + Windows, actively maintained, production-proven (Tauri 2.0 went stable Oct 2024, now widely used) |
| Frontend | **React + TypeScript + Vite** | Standard, fast dev loop, huge animation ecosystem |
| Package manager | **pnpm** | As requested — fast installs, efficient disk usage, good workspace support |
| Orb rendering | **react-three-fiber** (WebGL/Three.js) for the polished version; plain **Canvas2D** for the MVP | A shader-driven sphere gets you real "liquid glow" motion and amplitude-reactive distortion; Canvas2D is enough to get something on screen in day one |
| State (frontend) | **Zustand** | Minimal boilerplate, easy to update from Tauri event listeners |
| Audio capture | **cpal** (Rust) | True cross-platform audio I/O — CoreAudio backend on macOS, WASAPI on Windows — actively maintained, no Python dependency |
| Voice activity detection | **silero-vad-rs** (or equivalent, via the `ort` ONNX Runtime crate) | Filters silence before it ever reaches wake-word/STT, cuts CPU use dramatically for an always-on mic |
| Wake word | **oww-rs** (a Rust port of openWakeWord, via `ort`) | Ships a pre-trained `hey_jarvis` ONNX model out of the box — genuinely on-brand for this project, and you can train/swap in a custom wake word later via the original openWakeWord toolchain |
| Speech-to-text | **whisper-rs** (Rust bindings to whisper.cpp) | Fully local/offline, cross-platform (Windows MSVC, macOS Intel + Apple Silicon w/ Metal, Linux), GGML model files are portable binary blobs — the exact thing that lets you prep a model on Mac and ship the same file to Windows |
| ONNX inference runtime | **ort** (pykeio/ort, currently ~2.0 RC, wrapping ONNX Runtime) | Backs both VAD and wake word, cross-platform, GPU-optional |
| Dispatcher | Rust trait + pluggable implementation | Keeps "open claw" swappable — subprocess, HTTP, or SDK, decided later without touching the voice pipeline |
| CI / cross-platform builds | **GitHub Actions matrix** (`macos-latest` + `windows-latest`) with `tauri-action` | Real native builds on each OS — see [Section 8](#8-cross-platform-builds--testing-with-pnpm) for why this beats trying to cross-compile from a single Mac |

A note on why not Python anywhere in this stack: every model here (Whisper via whisper.cpp, Silero VAD, openWakeWord) has a mature, actively-maintained Rust binding that talks directly to compiled C/C++ or ONNX Runtime. That means your only toolchain to manage is Rust + Node, on both platforms — no bundling a Python interpreter and site-packages into a desktop installer, which is its own can of worms.

