## 5. The always-listening voice engine

### 5.1 State machine

This is the backbone everything else hangs off of — both the dispatcher and the orb animation are just *reactions to this state*, so get it right first.

```
IDLE ──(wake word detected)──► WAKE_DETECTED ──► LISTENING ──(VAD: user stopped talking,
  ▲                                                  │            or silence timeout)
  │                                                  ▼
  │                                            PROCESSING ──(STT done, text sent)──► DISPATCHING
  │                                                  │                                    │
  │                                                  │                                    ▼
  │                                                  │                              RESPONDING
  │                                                  │                                    │
  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────┘
                                (back to IDLE, or ERROR on any failure)
```

- **IDLE** — mic is open, audio streams continuously through VAD and the wake-word model only. Nothing is recorded or transcribed yet. This is the cheapest state, CPU-wise.
- **WAKE_DETECTED** — brief transitional state (a few hundred ms) so the orb can visibly "wake up" before it starts actually recording the command.
- **LISTENING** — now actively buffering audio for Whisper. VAD is used here to know when the user has stopped speaking (trailing silence) so you don't wait for a fixed timeout on every single command.
- **PROCESSING** — Whisper runs on the buffered audio, produces text.
- **DISPATCHING** — text is handed to the command backend; this can take arbitrary time depending on what "open claw" does, so it's its own state (important for the orb — see §7).
- **RESPONDING** — result comes back; orb shows an "answer" animation; optionally TTS speaks it.
- **ERROR** — anything failed (no mic permission, STT error, dispatcher timeout); orb shows a distinct error pulse, then returns to IDLE.

Emit every transition as a Tauri event (`voice-state-changed`) with a payload — the front end never needs to guess state, it just reacts.

### 5.2 Audio capture (`cpal`)

```toml
# Cargo.toml
[dependencies]
cpal = "0.17"
```

```rust
// voice/capture.rs (sketch)
use cpal::traits::{DeviceTrait, HostTrait, StreamTrait};

pub fn start_input_stream(sender: tokio::sync::mpsc::Sender<Vec<f32>>) -> cpal::Stream {
    let host = cpal::default_host();
    let device = host.default_input_device().expect("no input device");
    let config = device.default_input_config().unwrap();

    let stream = device.build_input_stream(
        &config.into(),
        move |data: &[f32], _| {
            let _ = sender.try_send(data.to_vec());
        },
        move |err| eprintln!("audio stream error: {err}"),
        None,
    ).unwrap();

    stream.play().unwrap();
    stream
}
```

`cpal` uses CoreAudio on macOS and WASAPI on Windows under the hood — same Rust API, different backend at compile time, which is exactly the "write once, ship to both" property you want.

### 5.3 VAD + wake word (always running, cheap)

Both `silero-vad-rs` and `oww-rs` run on tiny ONNX models (a few MB each) via `ort`, CPU-only, and are cheap enough to run continuously on every audio chunk without noticeably taxing the machine. Practically:

- Feed 16kHz mono frames (resample if the device's native rate differs — `cpal` gives you the native config, you'll want a small resampler, e.g. `rubato`) into VAD first.
- Only run the wake-word model on frames VAD marks as speech — this alone cuts a large chunk of the idle CPU cost.
- `oww-rs` ships `hey_jarvis_v0.1.onnx` as a ready-to-use example model with strong accuracy out of the box, so your literal wake phrase can be "Hey Jarvis" from day one with no custom training. If you want a different phrase later, openWakeWord's training pipeline (Python, one-time, offline) produces a new `.onnx` file you drop into `models/` — the Rust inference side doesn't change.

### 5.4 Speech-to-text (`whisper-rs`)

```toml
[dependencies]
whisper-rs = "0.16"
```

```rust
// voice/stt.rs (sketch)
use whisper_rs::{WhisperContext, WhisperContextParameters, FullParams, SamplingStrategy};

pub struct Transcriber {
    ctx: WhisperContext,
}

impl Transcriber {
    pub fn new(model_path: &str) -> Self {
        let ctx = WhisperContext::new_with_params(model_path, WhisperContextParameters::default())
            .expect("failed to load whisper model");
        Self { ctx }
    }

    pub fn transcribe(&self, audio: &[f32]) -> String {
        let mut state = self.ctx.create_state().expect("failed to create state");
        let params = FullParams::new(SamplingStrategy::Greedy { best_of: 1 });
        state.full(params, audio).expect("transcription failed");

        let num_segments = state.full_n_segments().unwrap_or(0);
        (0..num_segments)
            .filter_map(|i| state.full_get_segment_text(i).ok())
            .collect::<Vec<_>>()
            .join(" ")
    }
}
```

**Model size tradeoff** — pick based on the hardware you expect users to have:

| Model | Approx size | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `tiny` / `tiny.en` | ~75 MB | Fastest, noticeably worse accuracy on accents/noise |
| `base` / `base.en` | ~140 MB | Good default for a command-style assistant (short utterances, limited vocabulary of intents) |
| `small` / `small.en` | ~460 MB | Better accuracy, still real-time on most modern laptops |

Start with `base.en` (assuming English commands) — it's the sweet spot for short "Jarvis, do X" style utterances. Use the `.en` variants (English-only) over the multilingual ones — smaller and slightly faster for the same accuracy if you don't need other languages.

**On acceleration**: `whisper-rs` exposes `metal` and `cuda` feature flags. Enable `metal` when building on macOS for real-time performance on Apple Silicon; on Windows, either ship the CPU-only build (fine for `base`/`small` on modern CPUs) or gate a `cuda` build behind detecting an NVIDIA GPU if you want to optimize further later. Don't over-engineer this on day one — CPU inference for `base.en` is fast enough for a command assistant on both platforms.

### 5.5 The critical portability point

**Model files are portable; the inference binary is not.** This is worth being precise about since it's exactly what you asked for:

- A GGML Whisper model (`ggml-base.en.bin`) or an ONNX model (`hey_jarvis_v0.1.onnx`, `silero_vad.onnx`) is a plain binary blob of weights. You download or prepare it once — on your Mac, it doesn't matter — and the *identical file* works on Windows. There's no "recompiling the model" step, ever.
- What *does* need to be built separately per OS is the Rust binary that loads and runs those models (because it links against platform-specific system libraries — CoreAudio vs. WASAPI, Metal vs. CPU/CUDA paths in whisper.cpp, etc.). That's a `cargo build --release` per target OS, not a cross-compilation of the models.
- Practical workflow: keep the model files in `src-tauri/models/` in your repo (or fetch them in a build step — see §8), and let Tauri's bundler package them into both the `.dmg`/`.app` and the `.msi`/`.exe` installers automatically. Same files, two installers.

