## 7. The Jarvis orb (front end)

### 7.1 Rendering approach

Two viable paths, pick based on how much polish you want on day one vs. later:

- **MVP: Canvas2D.** A radial gradient circle with `shadowBlur` for glow, animated via `requestAnimationFrame`, amplitude driving scale/opacity. You can have something on screen and reactive within a day.
- **Polished: WebGL via `react-three-fiber`.** A sphere with a custom fragment shader (noise-based surface distortion + fresnel glow), amplitude and frequency data driving vertex displacement uniforms in real time. This is what gives the "liquid, alive" look closer to Iron Man's Jarvis or Siri's orb, at the cost of writing (or adapting) a GLSL shader.

Recommended sequencing: build the Canvas2D version first so the state machine → animation wiring is proven end-to-end, then swap the rendering internals for the shader version once the rest of the app works. The React component's *interface* (props: `state`, `amplitude`, `frequencyBands`) doesn't need to change between the two.

### 7.2 State → visual mapping

| Voice state | Orb behavior |
|---|---|
| `IDLE` | Slow ambient "breathing" — gentle scale/opacity pulse, cool color (blue/cyan), low-frequency sine wave, no audio reactivity |
| `WAKE_DETECTED` | Sharp brightening flash, color shift, quick scale-up — this is the "it heard you" moment, keep it snappy (<300ms) |
| `LISTENING` | Amplitude-reactive distortion/glow — orb visibly responds to the user's voice in real time, using the amplitude/frequency data streamed from Rust |
| `PROCESSING` | Different rhythm — a steady rotating/pulsing pattern *not* tied to live audio (since nothing's being said), signaling "thinking" |
| `DISPATCHING` | Continues the "thinking" motion, possibly slower/deeper — this can be the longest state depending on the backend, so make it read as "still working," not "stuck" |
| `RESPONDING` | Distinct color (e.g. warm amber/green) with an outward pulse or ripple — the clear "answer accepted" moment the request asked for |
| `ERROR` | Short red flash, then decay back to `IDLE` — must be visually distinct from all the above so users never confuse a failure with normal operation |

### 7.3 Audio-reactive data flow

Don't re-capture the mic in the webview — the Rust core already has it. Instead, have the voice engine compute a lightweight amplitude (RMS) and a few frequency bands (a small FFT, e.g. via the `rustfft` crate) per audio chunk, and emit them:

```rust
// inside the voice engine loop
app_handle.emit("voice-audio-level", AudioLevel {
    amplitude: rms,
    bands: [low, mid, high],
})?;
```

```ts
// tauriEvents.ts
import { listen } from '@tauri-apps/api/event';

listen<AudioLevel>('voice-audio-level', (event) => {
  voiceStore.getState().setAudioLevel(event.payload);
});

listen<VoiceState>('voice-state-changed', (event) => {
  voiceStore.getState().setState(event.payload);
});
```

Throttle this to ~30–60 updates/sec (not every raw audio callback) so you're not flooding the IPC bridge — plenty smooth for orb animation, negligible overhead.

