## 9. Phased build plan

A sensible order that gets you a working (if rough) end-to-end loop as early as possible, then layers polish on top:

1. **Skeleton app** — `pnpm create tauri-app`, confirm it builds and runs on macOS. Static placeholder orb (just a div/circle) so the shell is proven.
2. **Audio capture only** — wire up `cpal`, confirm you can capture and log raw mic levels from Rust, emit amplitude to the front end, make the placeholder orb pulse with it. This proves the whole Rust↔JS event bridge.
3. **VAD** — add `silero-vad-rs`, log speech/silence segments to the console. No behavior change yet, just validate detection quality on your own voice/room.
4. **Wake word** — add `oww-rs` with the bundled `hey_jarvis` model, wire the `IDLE → WAKE_DETECTED` transition, confirm reliability (test false-positive/false-negative rate in your actual environment).
5. **STT** — add `whisper-rs`, wire `LISTENING → PROCESSING`, get raw transcribed text printed to console/UI. This is the first point where you have a full "say something, see it as text" loop.
6. **Dispatcher stub** — a fake `CommandBackend` that just echoes the text back, wire the full state machine end-to-end (`IDLE → ... → RESPONDING → IDLE`).
7. **Real orb** — replace the placeholder with the actual Canvas2D (then later WebGL) reactive design from §7.
8. **Real dispatcher** — swap the stub for the actual "open claw" integration once that's defined.
9. **Cross-platform CI** — set up the GitHub Actions matrix, get a Windows build produced and tested (VM or hardware).
10. **Polish pass** — settings panel (mic device selection, model size choice, wake-word sensitivity), error states, optional TTS for responses, signing.

